data.content:
Here's the complete migration:

## Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

If `work` itself is long-running, add a `CancellationToken` overload so it can **cooperate**:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.WaitAsync` only abandons the *wait* — the delegate keeps running on the thread pool. The `Func<T>` must check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals for work to truly stop. |
| **Blocking I/O won't cancel** | Synchronous calls like `Thread.Sleep` or `socket.Receive` ignore the token. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O that accepts a `CancellationToken`. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer leaks. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout, not unrelated cancellations. |
| **Token not forwarded through call chain** | Every method in the chain must accept and pass the token. One gap = cancellation stalls there. |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If `work` calls third-party code you can't modify, cooperative cancellation won't help. Move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only safe equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort`. |

## What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable wait without dedicated thread |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (automatic via timeout) | Cooperative cancellation replaces forcible abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No abort to reset — code checks `IsCancellationRequested` and decides whether to continue |
